Tony Stark, also known as Iron Man, is a fictional character in the Marvel Comics universe and the Marvel Cinematic Universe (MCU). Created by writer Stan Lee, scripter Larry Lieber, and artists Don Heck and Jack Kirby, Tony Stark made his first appearance in "Tales of Suspense" #39 in 1963.

In both the comics and the MCU, Tony Stark is portrayed as a genius inventor and billionaire industrialist who inherits Stark Industries, a multinational conglomerate involved in advanced technology and weapons manufacturing. After being captured and held captive by terrorists, he creates a powered suit of armor to escape, marking the birth of Iron Man. He later refines the suit and uses it to protect the world as a superhero.

Key aspects of Tony Stark's character include his quick wit, charismatic personality, and his struggle with his own humanity while balancing his responsibilities as both a businessman and a superhero. Throughout his story arcs, Stark deals with issues such as alcoholism, morality, and the consequences of his technology.
column54:
In the MCU, Tony Stark is portrayed by Robert Downey Jr., who played a pivotal role in establishing the character's popularity and contributing significantly to the success of the franchise. Stark's character arc in the MCU spans from being a self-centered playboy to a selfless hero willing to sacrifice himself for the greater good, culminating in his iconic role in the Avengers team and his ultimate sacrifice in "Avengers: Endgame."

Overall, Tony Stark/Iron Man is a complex and iconic character known for his intelligence, innovation, and evolution throughout various comic book storylines and cinematic adaptations.
